 come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Sibilla","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]},{"name":"Sybille","meanings":["From Greek.  See  <b>Sybil</b> ."]},{"name":"Sibella","meanings":["From the name (Greek <i>Sibylla</i> or <i>Sybilla</i>, with confusion over the vowels from an early period) of a class of ancient prophetesses inspired by Apollo. According to medieval theology, they were pagans denied the knowledge of Christ but blessed by God with some insight into things to come and accordingly admitted to heaven. It was thus regarded as a respectable name to be borne by Christians. This name was introduced to England by the Normans and enjoyed considerable popularity in the Middle Ages."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Sybil was born in 1134, in Buckinghamshire, England, United Kingdom. She had at least 1 son with Simon de Hampden. She died in 1147, in her hometown, at the age of 13."},"et":{"1134–1147":"1134–1147","1130–1147":"1130–1147","1148–1204":"1148–1204","1204":"1204","1148":"1148","1147":"1147","1134":"1134","1130":"1130","Abt 1147":"umbes 1147","Buckinghamshire, England":"Buckinghamshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1134–1147":"1134–1147","1130–1147":"1130–1147","1148–1204":"1148–1204","1204":"1204","1148":"1148","1147":"1147","1134":"1134","1130":"1130","Abt 1147":"noin 1147","Buckinghamsh